Oh, okay.

00:08:16.399 --> 00:08:20.399
Would you like to learn how to be part of that future?

00:08:20.399 --> 00:08:21.399
Uh, yeah.

00:08:21.399 --> 00:08:22.399
Um, thanks.

00:08:22.399 --> 00:08:25.399
I'm not really the chatty type.

00:08:25.399 --> 00:08:28.399
And I'm late, so see you later.

00:08:28.399 --> 00:08:38.679
Did you notice how Nita prefaced some of her questions?

00:08:38.679 --> 00:08:40.679
Did you know?

00:08:40.679 --> 00:08:43.679
Did you know the Bible says you can live forever?

00:08:43.679 --> 00:08:48.679
No, I mean, did you know the Bible says you can live forever on earth?

00:08:48.679 --> 00:08:53.679
A thought-provoking question to get the conversation started.

00:08:53.679 --> 00:08:57.679
Now, maybe it's been a little while since you were able to stand in a public place with a

00:08:57.679 --> 00:09:00.679
witnessing card as we saw Nita doing here.

00:09:00.679 --> 00:09:06.679
But we can have conversations on the phone, perhaps in stores, in the park.

00:09:06.679 --> 00:09:09.679
Questions also work well in letters.

00:09:09.679 --> 00:09:13.679
Of course, it's easy for us to think of questions on topics that interest us.

00:09:13.679 --> 00:09:20.679
But what is needed is to think of questions that others will enjoy answering.

00:09:20.679 --> 00:09:28.679
Such questions as, did you know that the Bible describes a time when sickness will be no more?

00:09:28.679 --> 00:09:32.679
Do you think we'll ever see true economic security?

00:09:32.679 --> 00:09:35.679
It would be nice to be able to plan.

00:09:35.679 --> 00:09:40.679
What do you think is a reliable source of information about the future?

00:09:40.679 --> 00:09:45.679
Do you think we could be living in what the Bible calls the last days?

00:09:45.679 --> 00:09:50.679
I've noticed that many people still pray, especially when they have problems.

00:09:50.679 --> 00:09:54.679
Do you think anyone listens to prayers?

00:09:54.679 --> 00:09:57.679
Does God listen to all prayers?

00:09:57.679 --> 00:09:59.679
Viewpoint questions.

00:09:59.679 --> 00:10:03.679
Viewpoint questions invite people to express their thoughts.

00:10:03.679 --> 00:10:08.679
Often, Jesus would pause, ask people what they thought,

00:10:08.679 --> 00:10:11.679
and then listen to their response.

00:10:11.679 --> 00:10:18.679
For example, after the death of Martha's brother Lazarus, Jesus told her as recorded in John chapter 11 verses 25 and 26.

00:10:18.679 --> 00:10:23.679
Everyone who was living and exercises faith in me will never die at all.

00:10:23.679 --> 00:10:26.679
But then he asked her,

00:10:26.679 --> 00:10:30.679
Do you believe this?

00:10:30.679 --> 00:10:34.679
Do you believe this?

00:10:34.679 --> 00:10:38.679
And then he listened, as she expressed her faith.

00:10:38.679 --> 00:10:43.679
This type of question can be very effective in our disciple-making work.

00:10:43.679 --> 00:10:48.679
Or, like Jesus, we can use a series of questions to help people reason.

00:10:48.679 --> 00:10:52.679
In the video, did you notice how after reading Revelation 214,

00:10:52.679 --> 00:10:54.679
Nita asked Jade,

00:10:54.679 --> 00:10:59.679
Since there's no death or pain in heaven, where would this promise apply?

00:10:59.679 --> 00:11:01.679
And then she asked,

00:11:01.679 --> 00:11:05.679
Would you like to learn how to be a part of that future?

00:11:05.679 --> 00:11:10.679
We improve our skills by imitating Jesus.

00:11:10.679 --> 00:11:14.679
And as our skill improves, our joy increases.

00:11:14.679 --> 00:11:18.679
Jesus delighted to make disciples and we can too.

00:11:18.679 --> 00:11:22.679
By asking questions and then listening to people's answers,

00:11:22.679 --> 00:11:25.679
we may help some of them to accept the good news.

00:11:25.679 --> 00:11:32.679
And we will definitely experience first hand the joy of disciple-making.

